<note id="fs-id1167470700235" class="astronomy link-to-learning">
<para id="fs-id1167471062247">Check out this <link url="https://openstaxcollege.org/l/30JWSTdiag">fun diagram</link> comparing the sizes of the largest planned and existing telescopes to a regulation basketball and tennis court.</para>
</note>
<section id="fs-id1167470625224" class="summary"><title>Summary</title><list id="eip-idm1076198128"><item>New and even larger telescopes are on the drawing boards.</item><item>The James Webb Space Telescope, a 6-meter successor to Hubble, is currently scheduled for launch in 2021.</item><item>Gamma-ray astronomers are planning to build the CTA to measure very energetic gamma rays.</item><item>Astronomers are building the LSST to observe with an unprecedented field of view and a new generation of visible-light/infrared telescopes with apertures of 24.5 to 39 meters in diameter.</item></list>
